To simplify matters, let \(f(x, y) = \frac{x - y}{x^4 + y^4 + 6}\). To find critical points, compute \(\nabla f(x, y)\):
\[\nabla f(x, y) = \left(\frac{-y^4 + 4xy^3 + 6 - 4x^3y}{(x^4 + y^4 + 6)^2}, -\frac{x^4 - 4x^3y + y^4 + 6 - 4xy^3}{(x^4 + y^4 + 6)^2}\right)\]For possible extrema, set partial derivatives equal to zero (\(\partial f / \partial x = 0\) and \(\partial f / \partial y = 0\) ) simultaneously:\[
    \begin{array}{rcl}
      -y^4 + 4xy^3 + 6 - 4x^3y &=& 0 \\
      -(x^4 - 4x^3y + y^4 + 6 - 4xy^3) &=& 0 \\
     \end{array}
